    intro: "France imposes no restrictions on foreign property ownership, but the purchase process, fee structure, and tax implications have specific features that catch many buyers off guard. This guide covers everything from the compromis to the acte authentique.",
    readMinutes: 11,
    sections: [
      {
        heading: "Can foreigners buy property in France?",
        body: "Yes, unconditionally. France imposes no restriction on property ownership by foreigners: non-residents and non-EU nationals can buy freehold property (pleine propriété) on identical terms to French citizens. There is no minimum residency requirement, no land ownership ceiling, and no foreign buyer surcharge. This distinguishes France from countries like Australia, Canada (with new restrictions), or Denmark (which requires EU/EEA residency). The purchase process is identical regardless of nationality. The key variable is your mortgage eligibility, which French banks assess more conservatively for non-residents.",
      },
      {
        heading: "The purchase process — from offer to completion",
        body: "Step 1, the Compromis de vente: once your offer is accepted, you sign a preliminary contract (compromis or promesse de vente) and pay a deposit of 5 to 10% of the purchase price. This is binding, and the seller cannot accept another offer. The buyer has a 10-day cooling-off period (délai de rétractation) to withdraw without penalty. Step 2, the due diligence period (3 to 4 months): the notaire (state-certified solicitor) checks title, searches for encumbrances, and orders mandatory diagnostic reports (DPE, amiante, plomb, termites, and others). Your mortgage offer is firmed up. Step 3, the Acte authentique: the final signing at the notaire's office, where the full purchase price plus fees are paid and keys are handed over. The notaire registers the title change with the land registry (publicité foncière). The process typically takes 3 to 4 months from accepted offer to completion, or 2 months if there is no mortgage.",
      },
      {
        heading: "The notaire — what they do and why you need them",
        body: "The notaire is a state official who certifies the transaction, holds funds in escrow, performs all legal checks, and registers the transfer. Their involvement is mandatory for any property transaction in France. On costs, notaire fees (frais de notaire) are set by law and paid by the buyer, typically 7 to 8% of the purchase price for older properties (resale) and 2 to 3% for new builds (TVA is already included in the price). On a €300,000 apartment, expect €21,000 to 24,000 in frais de notaire. This is not negotiable; it is state-set. The notaire represents both buyer and seller, but buyers are free to appoint their own notaire in addition (the fees are shared between the two, not doubled). For a non-French speaker, having your own notaire who speaks English and can explain documents is strongly recommended.",
      },
      {
        heading: "Getting a French mortgage as a non-resident",
        body: "French banks will lend to non-residents, but with stricter conditions. The key parameters: loan-to-value (LTV) typically capped at 70 to 80% for non-residents (versus 85 to 95% for French residents); a debt service ratio (taux d'endettement) capped at 35% of gross income; mandatory life insurance; and minimum income evidence (3 years of tax returns or pay slips). Interest rates in 2026: fixed rates typically run 3.5 to 4.5% depending on term and profile, over a 15 to 25 year term. On currency risk, French mortgages are in euros, so if your income is in GBP, USD, or CHF, factor in currency fluctuation. Non-resident mortgage specialists (Banque Transatlantique, Crédit Foncier, BNP International, HSBC France) are easier to deal with than retail branches, and online mortgage brokers (Meilleurtaux, Pretto) can also access non-resident products.",
      },
      {
        heading: "Taxes on French property",
        body: "Annual taxes start with the Taxe Foncière, the property tax paid by the owner, typically €500 to 3,000/year depending on property size and location. The Taxe d'Habitation has been abolished for primary residences since 2023 but still applies to second homes. Capital gains tax (plus-value immobilière) is a 19% flat rate for EU residents and 36.2% for non-EU non-residents, but with substantial abatements after 5 years of ownership: zero CGT after 22 years for income tax, and 30 years for social charges. On rental income, if you rent the property, income is subject to French income tax (on the 12.8 to 45% scale) and social charges (17.2%) for non-residents, totalling up to 27.5% on rental income. Double-tax treaties exist with most countries (UK, USA, Germany, and others), so consult a tax advisor. On inheritance tax, France taxes French real estate regardless of where the heir resides, and rates vary by relationship (0% for a spouse, up to 45% for unrelated parties).",
      },
      {
        heading: "Hidden costs and things agents won't mention",
        body: "Agency fees (honoraires d'agence) in France are often paid by the buyer, typically 3 to 8% of the purchase price. Listings marked «FAI» (frais d'agence inclus) include the fee in the listed price; listings without FAI mean the fee is added on top. Ask explicitly before making an offer. On copropriété charges, apartments in French buildings belong to a co-ownership structure (copropriété), and annual charges (charges de copropriété) cover maintenance, insurance, and shared utilities. Verify the last 3 years of accounts and any voted works (travaux votés) that you would inherit as the new owner. For renovation in protected zones, properties in secteurs sauvegardés (historic districts) require ABF (Architecte des Bâtiments de France) approval for any exterior work, which can be slow and constrain your choices. On the DPE rating, energy diagnostics are now binding: F and G-rated properties cannot have rents increased and face progressive rental bans, so buying an F/G requires a renovation budget.",
      },
      {
        heading: "Practical tips for non-resident buyers",
        body: "Use a bilingual notaire or appoint your own alongside the seller's; most notaires in tourist areas (Côte d'Azur, Brittany, Dordogne) have English-speaking staff. Open a French bank account before starting your search, because some vendors and all notaires require a French IBAN for the deposit. Visit in person, since you should never buy French property from photos alone. Book a full survey (expertise immobilière) beyond the mandatory diagnostics, because the diagnostics reveal risks, not structural defects. Check the Plan Local d'Urbanisme (PLU) if buying land or planning to extend, since building rights are tightly regulated. For rural properties, check the SAFER right of pre-emption (the agricultural land protection body can pre-empt rural sales in some cases). For currency transfer, use a specialist FX service (Wise, Moneycorp, Currencies Direct) rather than a retail bank; on a €300,000 transfer, saving 1% on exchange rates is €3,000.",
      },
    ],
